k contradicting one another, thereby undermining their credibility and potential to bring about real change on the ground: Where some committees view religion singularly as a core individual right, others see religion partly as an inherent threat to the realization of other rights, but also as a potent social force to be reckoned with. In order to remedy this situation, Årsheim proposes the publication of a joint general comment by all the committees, spelling out their approach to the role of religion in the implementation of human rights.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified individually in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aFreedom of religion (International law) 0aFreedom of religion (International law). 0aReligion and international relations. 0aReligion and law. 0aReligious discriminationxLaw and legislation. 0aReligious minoritiesxLegal status, laws, etc. 4aMenschenrechte. 4aRechtswesen. 4aReligion. 4aVereinte Nationen. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh  aLaw.  aUnited Nations.  ahuman rights.  areligion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2018 Part 1z978311076248808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2018z97831107195500 cEPUBz97831104765900 cprintz978311047653840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110478068zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110478068zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110478068/original  a978-3-11-071955-0 DG Plus eBook-Package 2018